page.title: 01CLEETHORPES GAZETTEER
page.content: The area lies on the south bank of the Humber estuary, in the County of Humberside. Much of the land is flat and was formerly marshland. Only on the ridge which runs from west to east across the area in the south, ending in a cliff overlooking the Humber, does the land rise above the 10m contour. Administratively the area is divided between the towns of Grimsby and Cleethorpes, although most visitors would find it difficult to see where one town ended and the other began. In the north east of the area lie the Grimsby fish docks, now much less prosperous than formerly. To the south east is the resort of Cleethorpes. In the south west is a new industrial area and, between that and Cleethorpes, the "village" of Old Clee.
